line of Bordeaux#Bibliography|l1=Bibliography of the history of Bordeaux}}\n\n* {{cite book\n|author= Chantal Callais and Thierry Jeanmonod\n|title= Bordeaux : a history of architecture\n|edition= \n|publisher= La Geste\n|location = La Cr\u00e8che\n|year= 2019\n|isbn= 979-10-353-0188-0\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|author= Fran\u00e7ois Hubert, Christian Block and Jacques de Cauna\n|title= Bordeaux in the 18th century : trans-Atlantic trading and slavery\n|edition= 2nd\n|publisher= Le Festin\n|location = Bordeaux\n|year= 2018\n|isbn= 978-2-36062-009-8\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons|Bordeaux}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Bordeaux}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130306023822/http://www.france.fr/en/regions-and-cities/bordeaux-world-capital-wine Bordeaux : the world capital of wine] \u2013 Official French website (in English)\n*{{Official website|1=www.bordeaux.fr|2=Bordeaux city council website}}\n*[http://www.bordeaux-tourisme.com/ Tourist office website]\n*[http://www.phonebookofbordeaux.com/ Phonebook of Bordeaux]\n*[https://archive.today/20130205005719/http://www.uboat-bases.com/en/Bordeaux/la-base-de-u-boote-de-bordeaux.html Bordeaux submarine base : history, description, photos]\n*[http://www.girondins.com/ Official Girondins de Bordeaux website]\n*[http://www.sciencespo.fr/ Sciences Po Bordeaux]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060421221321/http://www.infotbc.com/ Tram and bus maps and schedules]\n*[http://www.bordeaux.com/ Bordeaux Wine official website]\n*[http://www.bordeaux-gironde.fr/ Map & City guide website]\n*[http://www.battlefieldsww2.com/Bordeaux_u-boat_bunker.html German submarine base in Bordeaux]\n*[https://www.bordeaux-port.fr/en/port-bordeaux/history]\n{{Cities in France}}\n{{Gironde communes}}\n{{Urban Community of Bordeaux}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in France}}\n{{Higher Education in Bordeaux}}\n{{Prefectures of departments of France}}\n{{Prefectures of regions of France}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bordeaux| ]]<!--leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Communes of Gironde]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns on the French Atlantic coast]]\n[[Category:Prefectures in France]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in France]]\n[[Category:Cities in France]]\n[[Category:Gironde]]\n[[Category:Guyenne]]\n[[Category:Burdigalian| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jefunky", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bordeaux"}
{"title_page": "Robert Pho", "text_new": "{{notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Robert Pho\n|home_town    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n|nationality   = [[Cambodian American]]\n|occupation    = [[Tattoo artist]]<br>[[graffiti]] artist\n|website       = \n}}\n'''Robert Pho''' is an internationally recognised and award winning black and gray [[Tattoo artist|tattoo artists]] from Las Vegas, USA.<ref>{{cite news |title=Walk on the Dark Side with This STAR WARS Tattoo |url=https://nerdist.com/article/walk-on-the-dark-side-with-this-star-wars-tattoo/ |work=[[Nerdist.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Louie |first1=Tim |title=Inked Out: Skin Design Tattoo \u2013 Las Vegas, NV |url=https://www.theaquarian.com/2016/12/07/inked-out-skin-design-tattoo-las-vegas-nv/ |work=[[The Aquarian Weekly]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Pho was born in [[Cambodia]]. At the age of 2 years, he had to move to France with his parents to avoid the [[Cambodian Civil War]]. When he was 10 years old, he came to [[Los Angeles]], United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=Devon |title=Celebrate Asian American Heritage Month With 23 Badass Artists |url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/asianamericanheritagemonth |work=[[Inked (magazine)]] |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter getting out of prison in 1995, Robert started his career as a typist for livelihood besides tattooing his friends. He started tattooing in the year 1989.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview with Legendary Tattoo Artist Robert Pho |url=https://leadthefollowers.com/interview-with-legendary-artist-robert-pho/ |website=Lead The Followers |date=4 September 2018}}</ref> \n\nHe has tattooed the bodies of Filip Leu, [[Paul Booth (tattoo artist)|Paul Booth]], [[Jack Rudy]], Tom Renshaw, [[Robert Hernandez]], Kore Flatmo, [[Bob Tyrrell]], [[Nikko Hurtado]], [[Carlos Torres]], Joe Capobianco, Mike Devries, Roman Abrego, Tommy Montoya, Fernie Andrade, Brian Gonzalez, Chente, Bobby Serna, Chuey Quintanar, Fred Flores, Josh Duffy, Boris, Abey Alvarez, & Andy Pho.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adamakos |first1=Tess |title=Who's Tattooed The World's 10 Leading Tattoo Artists? |url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/10-tattoo-artists-wear-tattoos |work=[[Inked (magazine)]] |language=en}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Robert Pho\n|home_town    = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n|nationality   = [[Cambodian American]]\n|occupation    = [[Tattoo artist]]<br>[[graffiti]] artist\n|website       = \n}}\n'''Robert Pho''' is an internationally recognised and award winning black and gray [[Tattoo artist|tattoo artists]] from Las Vegas, USA.<ref>{{cite news |title=Walk on the Dark Side with This STAR WARS Tattoo |url=https://nerdist.com/article/walk-on-the-dark-side-with-this-star-wars-tattoo/ |work=[[Nerdist.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Louie |first1=Tim |title=Inked Out: Skin Design Tattoo \u2013 Las Vegas, NV |url=https://www.theaquarian.com/2016/12/07/inked-out-skin-design-tattoo-las-vegas-nv/ |work=[[The Aquarian Weekly]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Pho was born in [[Cambodia]]. At the tender age of 2 years, he had to move to France with his parents to avoid the [[Cambodian Civil War]]. When he was 10 years old, he came to [[Los Angeles]], United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Preston |first1=Devon |title=Celebrate Asian American Heritage Month With 23 Badass Artists |url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/asianamericanheritagemonth |work=[[Inked (magazine)]] |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter getting out of prison in 1995, Robert started his career as a typist for livelihood besides tattooing his friends. He started tattooing in the year 1989.<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview with Legendary Tattoo Artist Robert Pho |url=https://leadthefollowers.com/interview-with-legendary-artist-robert-pho/ |website=Lead The Followers |date=4 September 2018}}</ref> \n\nHe has tattooed the bodies of Filip Leu, [[Paul Booth (tattoo artist)|Paul Booth]], [[Jack Rudy]], Tom Renshaw, [[Robert Hernandez]], Kore Flatmo, [[Bob Tyrrell]], [[Nikko Hurtado]], [[Carlos Torres]], Joe Capobianco, Mike Devries, Roman Abrego, Tommy Montoya, Fernie Andrade, Brian Gonzalez, Chente, Bobby Serna, Chuey Quintanar, Fred Flores, Josh Duffy, Boris, Abey Alvarez, & Andy Pho.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adamakos |first1=Tess |title=Who's Tattooed The World's 10 Leading Tattoo Artists? |url=https://www.inkedmag.com/original-news/10-tattoo-artists-wear-tattoos |work=[[Inked (magazine)]] |language=en}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "SoCalDogLover", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Pho"}
{"title_page": "1973 Cardiff City Council election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''1973 Cardiff City Council election''' was held on Thursday 10 May 1973 to elect councillors to the new [[Cardiff City Council|Cardiff District Council]]<ref name=\"SWE carve out\">{{cite news|author= |title='Carve out' claim smashed by Labour's win |work=[[South Wales Echo]] |date= 11 May 1973 |page=18 }}</ref> (later to become known as Cardiff City Council) in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]]. It took place on the same day as other district council elections in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nThese were the first elections to the new district council, which would come into effect on 1 April 1974. The previous all-Cardiff elections to the old [[Cardiff City Council, 1905-1974|Cardiff City Council]] took place [[1972 Cardiff City Council election|in May 1972]]. Future elections would take place every three years, with the next election scheduled for [[1976 Cardiff City Council election|6 May 1976]]. \n{{TOC right}}\n\nThe 1973 election saw the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] win a significant majority on the Council.\n\n==Background==\nPreviously a unitary authority from 1889, Cardiff's council was to become a second-tier district authority to [[South Glamorgan County Council]] from 1 April 1974. This followed local government reorganisation enacted by the [[Local Government Act 1972]]. The 1973 election was the first to the new local authority, with councillors acting in a shadow capacity until April 1974.<ref name=\"SWE carve out\" /> The [[1973 South Glamorgan County Council election|election to South Glamorgan County Council]] had taken place in April 1973, with many Cardiff councillors standing for election to this authority. \n\nUntil 1973, elections to Cardiff City Council had been annual, with each of the three ward councillors standing down for election in rotation. In May 1973 all ward councillors were elected at the same election, to sit for three years.\n\n==Wards==\nThe wards to the new council remained the same in 1973 as the previous Cardiff City Council, but with the addition of two new wards: Lisvane, Llanedeyrn and St Mellons (1 seat); and Radyr, St Fagans, Tongwynlais (2 seats). Fourteen of the wards continued to have three councillors, but five wards had their representation doubled to six councillors.\n\nThe position of [[alderman]] was to be abolished, with all members of the new council being elected ward councillors.\n\n==Results==\nContests took place in all except one of the wards at this election.<ref name=\"Elections Centre\">{{cite web|title=Cardiff Welsh District Council Election Results 1973-1991|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Cardiff-1973-1991.pdf |publisher=The Elections Centre ([[Plymouth University]]) |accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SWE results\">{{cite news|title=The New District Councils - Election Results - S. Glam. - Cardiff |work=South Wales Echo |date= 11 May 1973 |page=19 }}</ref><sup>(a)</sup>\nLabour won control of the new council.\n\n{{Election Summary Begin|title = Cardiff District Council election result 1973 <ref name=\"Elections Centre\"/>}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 42 \n  |gain       = 42\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A'' \n  |seats %    = 56.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 33\n  |gain       = 33\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A'' \n  |seats %    = 44.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = 0\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A''\n  |seats %    = 0.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Plaid Cymru\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = 0\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A'' \n  |seats %    = 0.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Communist Party of Great Britain\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = 0\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A'' \n  |seats %    = 0.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = 186\n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election Summary Party|\n  |party      = Independent politician\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = 0\n  |loss       = ''N/A''\n  |net        = ''N/A''\n  |seats %    = 0.0\n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = 91\n  |plus/minus = ''N/A''\n}}\n|}\n\n==Results by ward==\n===Adamsdown===\n{{Election box begin | title = [[Adamsdown (electoral ward)|Adamsdown]] (3 seats)<ref name=\"Elections Centre\"/>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = D. Evans <sup>+</sup>\n  |votes      = 1,139\n  |percentage = 74.2\n  |change     = ''N/A'' \n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = John Iorwerth Jones <sup>o</sup><sup>+</sup>\n  |votes      = 1,102\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =  \n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = R. M. Costley\n  |votes      = 1,046\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =  \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = E. C. Canning\n  |votes      = 306\n  |percentage = 19.9\n  |change     = ''N/A'' \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Independent politician\n  |candidate  = Thelma Mackie\n  |votes      = 91\n  |percentage = 5.9\n  |change     = ''N/A'' \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = \n  |percentage = 25.3\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n  |reg. electors = 6,071\n}}\n{{Election box new seat win|\n  |